<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<aiscript name="XMP.ProxyPilot" purpose="med" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="../../../libraries/aiscripts.xsd">
  <!--
    XMultiplayer proxy pilot: Dead Reckoning AI-script (Milestone A3). PLAUSIBLE,
    not VERIFIED, same status as every other mod file so far, see
    docs/A3-messprotokoll.md for the full assumption list and open-questions
    checklist. Named XMP.ProxyPilot (dot-separated, not underscore) to match the
    namespaced style real X4 AI-script names commonly use.

    Purpose (PlanMod.md A3): fly a remote player's proxy ship toward a continuously
    re-extrapolated target (last known position + velocity * elapsed time), instead
    of teleporting it on every network update (the A2 baseline). Only the TARGET
    changes on a network update; the engine's own flight controller is what produces
    smooth, frame-accurate movement toward that target (Kollisionsvermeidung bleibt
    aktiv, siehe "movement" unten; no collision-avoidance-disabling flag is passed).

    HIGHEST-RISK/LEAST-CONFIDENT PARTS OF THIS FILE (beyond the general "PLAUSIBLE,
    not VERIFIED" status shared with the MD files):
      - The <aiscript> root shape itself: whether a bare <params>/<init>/<do_while>
        structure (as used here) is valid for a simple standalone movement script,
        or whether X4 requires wrapping the main loop in <attention>/<properties>
        (a pattern more commonly seen in reactive/interrupt AI-scripts). Simplest
        structure chosen deliberately to minimize invented surface area.
      - Whether a proxy ship needs an assigned NPC pilot before an AI-script can fly
        it at all, or whether an AI-script can control the hull directly regardless
        of crew. XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn (XMP_Arena.xml) now calls an assumed
        create_pilot/add_pilot action before start_ai_script, purely defensively;
        it may turn out to be unnecessary (e.g. if create_ship's macro already
        implies a default crew for combat-capable ships), in which case removing it
        is the simplification to make first.
      - move.to.position as the movement action name/shape, and move.stop (used for
        the update-timeout case below) likewise.
      - Whether re-issuing move.to.position every retarget interval updates the
        ship's current move order in place, or queues a new one behind it (which
        would make the ship's flight path lag further and further behind reality).
        If it queues, the fix is to call move.stop immediately before each re-issue.
      - object.blackboard as the MD <-> AI-script data channel (see "Data channel"
        below); assumed to exist and be readable/writable from both script types,
        since MD variables ($XMP.* in XMP_Arena.xml) are not otherwise visible here.

    Data channel: mod/md/XMP_Arena.xml's XMP_Arena_HandleStateUpdate writes the
    latest known truth onto the proxy ship's OWN blackboard (not into an MD-side
    table), specifically because blackboard is the one channel this script and MD
    can both plausibly reach: $XMP_TargetPosX/Y/Z, $XMP_TargetVelX/Y/Z,
    $XMP_TargetRecvTime (game time the truth was received, already backdated by the
    agent's estimated one-way link latency; see XMP_Arena.xml's header comment
    for the "Position + Geschwindigkeitsvektor x Latenz" reasoning). This script
    reads them off "this" (the ship it is running on).

    Snap vs. fly decision: on each loop iteration, if $XMP_TargetRecvTime changed
    since this script last looked (i.e. a new update arrived), compare "this"'s
    actual current position to the freshly received true position. If the squared
    distance exceeds $SnapThresholdMeters^2, hard-teleport (set_object_position)
    instead of flying; covers reconnects, long update gaps, or the proxy having
    drifted off course after being blocked by collision avoidance for a while.
    Squared distance is compared (not the real distance) purely to avoid needing an
    assumed sqrt primitive; mathematically equivalent for a greater-than comparison.

    Update-timeout decision (distinct from the extrapolation horizon below): if
    NO update has arrived for longer than $UpdateTimeoutSec, this is no longer "a
    bit stale, keep extrapolating" but "the link is probably down"; flying further
    off a minutes-old data point would be actively misleading, so movement is
    stopped instead (move.stop) and the proxy holds its last position until either
    a fresh update or a despawn arrives.

    Tuning parameters (PlanMod.md A3 "Tuning"), overridable at start_ai_script time
    from XMP_Arena.xml, defaults chosen for a S/M-class dogfight-speed ship:
      - $ExtrapolationHorizonSec (default 1.5s): elapsed time since the last update
        is capped at this value before extrapolating, so a proxy doesn't keep flying
        further and further from its last known heading between updates. Also
        implicitly limits how far a single high-velocity (boost) update can
        extrapolate before the next real update arrives and corrects it.
      - $SnapThresholdMeters (default 500m): see "Snap vs. fly decision" above.
      - $UpdateTimeoutSec (default 5s): see "Update-timeout decision" above. Longer
        than $ExtrapolationHorizonSec on purpose: the horizon caps a single
        extrapolation step, the timeout is the much longer "give up entirely" cutoff.
      - $RetargetIntervalSec (default 0.3s): how often this script re-evaluates and
        re-issues the move order. Deliberately much slower than the 10Hz network
        rate; the engine's own flight model is what has to look smooth frame to
        frame, this loop only ever needs to nudge the target often enough that the
        ship doesn't visibly overshoot a stale point.

    Known, accepted limitation (PlanMod.md A3 "Verhalten bei Boost/harten Drehungen"):
    extrapolation assumes constant velocity between updates, so a hard turn or a
    boost/deceleration right after the last update we know about will show up as a
    brief, visible mispredict, corrected either by the next real update or (if bad
    enough) by the snap threshold above. Not solvable without a proper motion model;
    accepted per PlanMod.md 0.4/1.3 expectation management.
  -->
  <params>
    <param name="$ExtrapolationHorizonSec" default="1.5" />
    <param name="$SnapThresholdMeters" default="500" />
    <param name="$UpdateTimeoutSec" default="5" />
    <param name="$RetargetIntervalSec" default="0.3" />
  </params>

  <init>
    <do_all>
      <!-- -1 guarantees the first loop iteration treats whatever is on the
           blackboard (set once at spawn time, see XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn) as new. -->
      <set_value name="$LastSeenRecvTime" exact="-1" />
      <set_value name="$IsStopped" exact="false" />
    </do_all>
  </init>

  <do_while value="true">
    <do_all>
      <do_if value="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime != null and this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime != $LastSeenRecvTime">
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$DeltaX" exact="this.position.x - this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosX" />
          <set_value name="$DeltaY" exact="this.position.y - this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosY" />
          <set_value name="$DeltaZ" exact="this.position.z - this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosZ" />
          <set_value name="$DeviationSq" exact="$DeltaX * $DeltaX + $DeltaY * $DeltaY + $DeltaZ * $DeltaZ" />
          <do_if value="$DeviationSq &gt; $SnapThresholdMeters * $SnapThresholdMeters">
            <do_all>
              <set_object_position
                object="this"
                position="table[x=this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosX, y=this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosY, z=this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosZ]" />
              <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][ProxyPilot] snap teleport, deviation_sq=' + $DeviationSq" filter="general" />
            </do_all>
          </do_if>
          <set_value name="$LastSeenRecvTime" exact="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime" />
          <set_value name="$IsStopped" exact="false" />
        </do_all>
      </do_if>

      <do_if value="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime != null">
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$SinceLastUpdate" exact="player.age - this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime" />
          <!--
            do_if/else structure note: the true-branch below is a single <do_all>
            (containing a nested do_if with NO else of its own), so that <else>'s
            immediately preceding sibling is always a <do_all>, never a closed
            <do_if> element, matching the pattern used everywhere else in this
            codebase. An earlier version nested the "not $IsStopped" do_if directly
            as the outer do_if's true-branch with <else> as its next sibling; that
            reads as "else pairs with the outer do_if" by XML nesting, but X4's
            actual do_if/else pairing (per the A3 review) attaches <else> to
            whichever do_if is its nearest PRECEDING SIBLING in document order,
            here that was the inner "not $IsStopped" do_if, not the outer one.
            Effect of that bug: once stopped, every later iteration re-entered the
            (wrongly paired) "else" and flew off stale data again, while still
            logging "holding position" from the one-time transition; the log
            would have lied about what the ship was actually doing.
          -->
          <do_if value="$SinceLastUpdate &gt; $UpdateTimeoutSec">
            <do_all>
              <do_if value="not $IsStopped">
                <do_all>
                  <move.stop />
                  <set_value name="$IsStopped" exact="true" />
                  <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][ProxyPilot] no update for ' + $SinceLastUpdate + 's, holding position'" filter="general" />
                </do_all>
              </do_if>
            </do_all>
            <else>
              <do_all>
                <!-- A fresh update arrived after a timeout (or none happened yet):
                     make sure we're not left thinking we're still stopped. -->
                <set_value name="$IsStopped" exact="false" />
                <set_value name="$Elapsed" exact="min{value1=$SinceLastUpdate, value2=$ExtrapolationHorizonSec}" />
                <set_value name="$ExtrapolatedX" exact="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosX + this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelX * $Elapsed" />
                <set_value name="$ExtrapolatedY" exact="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosY + this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelY * $Elapsed" />
                <set_value name="$ExtrapolatedZ" exact="this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosZ + this.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelZ * $Elapsed" />
                <!-- No collision-avoidance-disabling attribute passed here on
                     purpose: PlanMod.md A3 requires the AI-script's own obstacle
                     avoidance to stay active, so this simply relies on the
                     action's default behavior. -->
                <move.to.position position="table[x=$ExtrapolatedX, y=$ExtrapolatedY, z=$ExtrapolatedZ]" />
              </do_all>
            </else>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </do_if>
    </do_all>
    <wait exact="$RetargetIntervalSec seconds" />
  </do_while>
</aiscript>
